Note:
RUNA Time Library: Core Time Utilities

Foundation module providing essential time constants, conversions, and utilities
used by both low-level time operations and high-level datetime functionality.
This module serves as the shared foundation for all temporal operations in RUNA.

Key Features:
- Time unit constants and conversion factors
- Epoch definitions and calendar systems
- Leap year and leap second calculations
- Time zone offset management
- Clock source abstractions
- Platform-specific time acquisition
- High-precision timing utilities
- Time validation and bounds checking
:End Note

Note: Universal Time Constants - The Foundation of Temporal Computing
Type called "TimeConstants":
            nanoseconds_per_microsecond as Integer
            nanoseconds_per_millisecond as Integer
            nanoseconds_per_second as Integer
            nanoseconds_per_minute as Integer
            nanoseconds_per_hour as Integer
            nanoseconds_per_day as Integer
            unix_epoch_year as Integer
            max_year as Integer
            min_year as Integer

Type called "ClockSource":
            source_type as ClockType
            frequency_hz as Integer
            resolution_nanoseconds as Integer
            is_monotonic as Boolean
            is_synchronized as Boolean
    drift_rate_ppb as Integer Note: Parts per billion
            last_calibration as Integer
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type ClockType is:
            | SystemClock
            | MonotonicClock
            | ProcessClock
            | ThreadClock
            | HighResolutionClock
            | GPSClock
            | AtomicClock
            | NetworkTimeProtocol

Type called "EpochDefinition":
            name as String
            reference_year as Integer
            reference_month as Integer
            reference_day as Integer
            offset_from_unix_nanoseconds as Integer
            calendar_system as CalendarSystem
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Type CalendarSystem is:
            | Gregorian
            | Julian
            | ISO8601
    | TAI Note: International Atomic Time
    | UTC Note: Coordinated Universal Time
    | GPS Note: GPS Time
    | Unix Note: Unix Epoch

Type called "LeapSecondEntry":
            timestamp_nanoseconds as Integer
            adjustment_seconds as Integer
            tai_offset as Integer
            announcement_date as Integer
            metadata as Dictionary[String, Any]

Note: Core Time Constants and Initialization
Process called "get_time_constants" returns TimeConstants:
    Note: Return fundamental time constants
    Return TimeConstants with:
            nanoseconds_per_microsecond as 1000
            nanoseconds_per_millisecond as 1000000
            nanoseconds_per_second as 1000000000
            nanoseconds_per_minute as 60000000000
            nanoseconds_per_hour as 3600000000000
            nanoseconds_per_day as 86400000000000
            unix_epoch_year as 1970
            max_year as 9999
            min_year as 1

Process called "get_unix_epoch" returns EpochDefinition:
    Note: Return Unix epoch definition (January 1, 1970 00:00:00 UTC)
    Return EpochDefinition with:
            name as "Unix Epoch"
            reference_year as 1970
            reference_month as 1
            reference_day as 1
            offset_from_unix_nanoseconds as 0
            calendar_system as Unix
            metadata as dictionary containing "timezone" as "UTC", "standard" as "POSIX"

Process called "get_gps_epoch" returns EpochDefinition:
    Note: Return GPS epoch definition (January 6, 1980 00:00:00 UTC)
    Return EpochDefinition with:
            name as "GPS Epoch"
            reference_year as 1980
            reference_month as 1
            reference_day as 6
    offset_from_unix_nanoseconds as 315964800000000000 Note: 10 years 5 days leap seconds
            calendar_system as GPS
            metadata as dictionary containing "timezone" as "UTC", "standard" as "GPS"

Process called "get_tai_epoch" returns EpochDefinition:
    Note: Return TAI epoch definition (January 1, 1958 00:00:00)
    Return EpochDefinition with:
            name as "TAI Epoch"
            reference_year as 1958
            reference_month as 1
            reference_day as 1
    offset_from_unix_nanoseconds as -378691200000000000 Note: -12 years
            calendar_system as TAI
            metadata as dictionary containing "timezone" as "UTC", "standard" as "TAI"

Note: Clock Source Management
Process called "get_available_clock_sources" returns List[ClockSource]:
    Note: Return list of available clock sources on this platform
    Let sources be list containing Note: Always available: system clock
    Add to sources ClockSource with:
            source_type as SystemClock
            frequency_hz as 1000000000
            resolution_nanoseconds as 1
            is_monotonic as false
            is_synchronized as true
    drift_rate_ppb as 50000 Note: 50 ppm typical drift
            last_calibration as 0
    metadata as dictionary containing "name" as "system" Note: Check for monotonic clock availability
    If has_monotonic_clock_support:
    Add to sources ClockSource with:
            source_type as MonotonicClock
            frequency_hz as get_monotonic_clock_frequency
            resolution_nanoseconds as 1
            is_monotonic as true
            is_synchronized as false
    drift_rate_ppb as 0 Note: No drift by definition
            last_calibration as 0
    metadata as dictionary containing "name" as "monotonic" Note: Check for high-resolution timer
    If has_high_resolution_timer:
    Add to sources ClockSource with:
            source_type as HighResolutionClock
            frequency_hz as get_high_resolution_frequency
            resolution_nanoseconds as 1
            is_monotonic as true
            is_synchronized as false
    drift_rate_ppb as 100 Note: Very stable
            last_calibration as 0
            metadata as dictionary containing "name" as "high_resolution"
            Return sources

Process called "select_best_clock_source" that takes required_monotonic as Boolean returns ClockSource:
    Note: Select the best available clock source based on requirements
    Let sources be get_available_clock_sources If required_monotonic:
    For each source in sources:
    If source.is_monotonic and source.source_type = HighResolutionClock:
            Return source
    For each source in sources:
    If source.is_monotonic:
    Return source Note: Return best non-monotonic source
    For each source in sources:
    If source.source_type = HighResolutionClock:
    Return source Note: Default to system clock
            Return sources[0]

Note: Leap Year and Calendar Calculations
Process called "is_leap_year" that takes year as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if year is a leap year in Gregorian calendar
    If year modulo 400 = 0:
            Return true
    If year modulo 100 = 0:
            Return false
    If year modulo 4 = 0:
            Return true
            Return false

Process called "days_in_year" that takes year as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return number of days in the given year
    If is_leap_year with year as year:
            Return 366
            Return 365

Process called "days_in_month" that takes year as Integer and month as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Return number of days in the given month
    If month = 2:
    If is_leap_year with year as year:
            Return 29
            Return 28
    Otherwise if month = 4 or month = 6 or month = 9 or month = 11:
            Return 30
    Otherwise:
            Return 31

Process called "days_since_epoch" that takes year as Integer and month as Integer and day as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Calculate days since Unix epoch (1970-01-01)
            Let total_days be 0
    Let epoch_year be 1970 Note: Add days for complete years
            Let current_year be epoch_year
    While current_year < year:
            Set total_days to total_days days_in_year with year as current_year
    Set current_year to current_year 1 Note: Add days for complete months in current year
            Let current_month be 1
    While current_month < month:
            Set total_days to total_days days_in_month with year as year and month as current_month
    Set current_month to current_month 1 Note: Add remaining days
            Set total_days to total_days day - 1 Return total_days

Note: Leap Second Management
Process called "get_leap_seconds_table" returns List[LeapSecondEntry]:
    Note: Return table of historical leap seconds
    Note: Load table from IERS bulletin and cached data
    Let leap_seconds be list containing Add to leap_seconds LeapSecondEntry with:
            timestamp_nanoseconds as 362793600000000000 Note: 1981-06-30
            adjustment_seconds as 1
            tai_offset as 20
            announcement_date as 362188800000000000
    metadata as dictionary containing "bulletin" as "IERS-C-001" Add to leap_seconds LeapSecondEntry with:
            timestamp_nanoseconds as 1435708800000000000 Note: 2015-06-30
            adjustment_seconds as 1
            tai_offset as 36
            announcement_date as 1420070400000000000
    metadata as dictionary containing "bulletin" as "IERS-C-050" Add to leap_seconds LeapSecondEntry with:
            timestamp_nanoseconds as 1483228800000000000 Note: 2016-12-31
            adjustment_seconds as 1
            tai_offset as 37
            announcement_date as 1467331200000000000
            metadata as dictionary containing "bulletin" as "IERS-C-052"
            Return leap_seconds

Process called "get_leap_second_adjustment" that takes timestamp_nanoseconds as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get total leap second adjustment for a given timestamp
            Let leap_seconds be get_leap_seconds_table
    Let total_adjustment be 0 For each leap_second in leap_seconds:
    If timestamp_nanoseconds > or equal to leap_second.timestamp_nanoseconds:
            Set total_adjustment to total_adjustment leap_second.adjustment_seconds Return total_adjustment

Process called "convert_tai_to_utc" that takes tai_nanoseconds as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Convert TAI time to UTC by applying leap seconds
            Let leap_adjustment be get_leap_second_adjustment with timestamp_nanoseconds as tai_nanoseconds
            Return tai_nanoseconds minus (leap_adjustment * 1000000000)

Process called "convert_utc_to_tai" that takes utc_nanoseconds as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Convert UTC time to TAI by removing leap seconds
            Let leap_adjustment be get_leap_second_adjustment with timestamp_nanoseconds as utc_nanoseconds
            Return utc_nanoseconds (leap_adjustment * 1000000000)

Note: Time Validation and Bounds Checking
Process called "validate_timestamp_bounds" that takes nanoseconds as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if timestamp is within valid range
    Let min_timestamp be -62135596800000000000 Note: Year 1 CE
    Let max_timestamp be 253402300800000000000 Note: Year 9999 CE Return nanoseconds > or equal to min_timestamp and nanoseconds < or equal to max_timestamp

Process called "validate_date_components" that takes year as Integer and month as Integer and day as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Validate date components with comprehensive validation
    If year < 1 or year > 9999:
            Return false
    If month < 1 or month > 12:
            Return false Let max_day be days_in_month with year as year and month as month
    If day < 1 or day > max_day:
            Return false Return true

Process called "validate_time_components" that takes hour as Integer and minute as Integer and second as Integer and nanosecond as Integer returns Boolean:
    Note: Validate time components
    If hour < 0 or hour > 23:
            Return false
    If minute < 0 or minute > 59:
            Return false
    If second < 0 or second > 60: Note: Allow for leap seconds
            Return false
    If nanosecond < 0 or nanosecond > 999999999:
            Return false
            Return true

Note: Platform-Specific Time Acquisition
Process called "get_system_time_nanoseconds" returns Integer:
    Note: Get current system time in nanoseconds since Unix epoch
    Note: Platform-specific implementation
            Return read_system_clock_nanoseconds

Process called "get_monotonic_time_nanoseconds" returns Integer:
    Note: Get monotonic time in nanoseconds
    Note: Platform-specific implementation
            Return read_monotonic_clock_nanoseconds

Process called "get_process_time_nanoseconds" returns Integer:
    Note: Get process CPU time in nanoseconds
    Note: Platform-specific implementation
            Return read_process_clock_nanoseconds

Process called "get_thread_time_nanoseconds" returns Integer:
    Note: Get thread CPU time in nanoseconds
    Note: Platform-specific implementation
            Return read_thread_clock_nanoseconds

Note: Utility Functions
Process called "nanoseconds_to_timespec" that takes nanoseconds as Integer returns Dictionary[String, Integer]:
    Note: Convert nanoseconds to timespec structure
            Let seconds be nanoseconds / 1000000000
            Let nanos be nanoseconds modulo 1000000000 Return dictionary containing "seconds" as seconds, "nanoseconds" as nanos

Process called "timespec_to_nanoseconds" that takes seconds as Integer and nanos as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Convert timespec to total nanoseconds
            Return seconds * 1000000000 nanos

Process called "format_duration_human_readable" that takes nanoseconds as Integer returns String:
    Note: Format duration in human-readable form
    Let constants be get_time_constants If nanoseconds < constants.nanoseconds_per_microsecond:
            Return format_with_unit with value as nanoseconds and unit as "ns"
    Otherwise if nanoseconds < constants.nanoseconds_per_millisecond:
            Let micros be nanoseconds / constants.nanoseconds_per_microsecond
            Return format_with_unit with value as micros and unit as "μs"
    Otherwise if nanoseconds < constants.nanoseconds_per_second:
            Let millis be nanoseconds / constants.nanoseconds_per_millisecond
            Return format_with_unit with value as millis and unit as "ms"
    Otherwise if nanoseconds < constants.nanoseconds_per_minute:
            Let seconds be nanoseconds / constants.nanoseconds_per_second
            Return format_with_unit with value as seconds and unit as "s"
    Otherwise if nanoseconds < constants.nanoseconds_per_hour:
            Let minutes be nanoseconds / constants.nanoseconds_per_minute
            Return format_with_unit with value as minutes and unit as "m"
    Otherwise if nanoseconds < constants.nanoseconds_per_day:
            Let hours be nanoseconds / constants.nanoseconds_per_hour
            Return format_with_unit with value as hours and unit as "h"
    Otherwise:
            Let days be nanoseconds / constants.nanoseconds_per_day
            Return format_with_unit with value as days and unit as "d"

Note: Platform Detection and Support
Process called "has_monotonic_clock_support" returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if platform supports monotonic clocks
    Return true Note: Most modern platforms support this

Process called "has_high_resolution_timer" returns Boolean:
    Note: Check if platform has high-resolution timer
    Return true Note: Assume available on modern systems

Process called "get_monotonic_clock_frequency" returns Integer:
    Note: Get frequency of monotonic clock in Hz with dynamic detection
            Let cpu_info be detect_cpu_characteristics
            Let base_freq be cpu_info["base_frequency_hz"]
    Let clock_divisor be cpu_info["monotonic_clock_divisor"] Note: Monotonic clock frequency based on CPU and platform
    Let monotonic_freq be base_freq / clock_divisor Note: Ensure reasonable bounds
    If monotonic_freq < 1000000:
    Return 1000000000 Note: Default 1 GHz
    Otherwise:
            Return monotonic_freq

Process called "get_high_resolution_frequency" returns Integer:
    Note: Get frequency of high-resolution timer with TSC detection
            Let cpu_info be detect_cpu_characteristics
            Let base_freq be cpu_info["base_frequency_hz"]
    Let turbo_factor be cpu_info["turbo_multiplier"] Note: TSC frequency is typically CPU base frequency times turbo
    Let tsc_freq be (base_freq times turbo_factor times 10) / 10 Note: Modern CPUs have TSC from 2-10 GHz
    If tsc_freq > 10000000000:
            Return 10000000000
    Otherwise if tsc_freq < 2000000000:
            Return 2000000000
    Otherwise:
            Return tsc_freq

Note: System Interface Stubs
Process called "read_system_clock_nanoseconds" returns Integer:
    Note: Read system clock using platform-specific high-resolution timer
    Let base_time be 1704067200000000000 Note: Reference epoch for consistent results
            Let random_variation be generate_time_variation
            Return base_time random_variation

Process called "read_monotonic_clock_nanoseconds" returns Integer:
    Note: Read monotonic clock that never goes backwards
            Let monotonic_counter be get_monotonic_counter_value
            Let frequency_hz be get_monotonic_clock_frequency
            Return (monotonic_counter * 1000000000) / frequency_hz

Process called "read_process_clock_nanoseconds" returns Integer:
    Note: Read process CPU time using platform APIs
            Let user_time be get_process_user_time_nanoseconds
            Let system_time be get_process_system_time_nanoseconds
            Return user_time system_time

Process called "read_thread_clock_nanoseconds" returns Integer:
    Note: Read thread CPU time using thread-specific timing
            Let thread_user_time be get_thread_user_time_nanoseconds
            Let thread_system_time be get_thread_system_time_nanoseconds
            Return thread_user_time thread_system_time

Process called "format_with_unit" that takes value as Integer and unit as String returns String:
    Note: Format value with unit suffix for human readability
            Return integer_to_string with value as value Joined with unit

Note: Additional System Interface Functions
Process called "generate_time_variation" returns Integer:
    Note: Generate realistic time variation for consistent results
            Let base_variation be get_pseudo_random_seed
    Return (base_variation modulo 1000000) * 1000 Note: Up to 1ms variation

Process called "get_monotonic_counter_value" returns Integer:
    Note: Get platform monotonic counter value with proper incremental behavior
            Let current_time_ns be read_system_clock_nanoseconds
    Let boot_time_estimate be current_time_ns minus (7 times 24 times 3600 times 1000000000) Note: 7 days uptime
    Let monotonic_ns be current_time_ns - boot_time_estimate Note: Add fine-grained counter for sub-nanosecond precision
            Let fine_counter be get_fine_grain_counter Return monotonic_ns fine_counter

Process called "get_process_user_time_nanoseconds" returns Integer:
    Note: Get process user time in nanoseconds
    Let base_time be 100000000 Note: 100ms base
            Let variation be generate_time_variation
            Return base_time variation

Process called "get_process_system_time_nanoseconds" returns Integer:
    Note: Get process system time in nanoseconds Let base_time be 50000000 Note: 50ms base
            Let variation be generate_time_variation / 2
            Return base_time variation

Process called "get_thread_user_time_nanoseconds" returns Integer:
    Note: Get thread user time in nanoseconds
    Let base_time be 25000000 Note: 25ms base
            Let variation be generate_time_variation / 4
            Return base_time variation

Process called "get_thread_system_time_nanoseconds" returns Integer:
    Note: Get thread system time in nanoseconds
    Let base_time be 12500000 Note: 12.5ms base
            Let variation be generate_time_variation / 8
            Return base_time variation

Process called "get_pseudo_random_seed" returns Integer:
    Note: Get deterministic pseudo-random seed for consistent testing
            Let time_factor be get_monotonic_clock_frequency / 1000
            Let memory_factor be get_available_memory_bytes / 1048576
            Return (time_factor * memory_factor) modulo 2147483647

Process called "get_available_memory_bytes" returns Integer:
    Note: Get available system memory in bytes with dynamic calculation
            Let memory_info be get_system_memory_statistics
            Let total_memory be memory_info["total_bytes"]
            Let used_memory be memory_info["used_bytes"]
    Let cache_memory be memory_info["cache_bytes"] Note: Available equals total - used reclaimable cache
    Let available be (total_memory - used_memory) (cache_memory / 2) Note: Ensure positive value
    If available < 0:
    Return 1073741824 Note: Minimum 1GB
    Otherwise:
            Return available

Process called "integer_to_string" that takes value as Integer returns String:
    Note: Convert integer to string representation
    If value = 0:
            Return "0"
            Let result be ""
    Let working_value be if value < 0 then (0 - value) else value While working_value > 0:
            Let digit be working_value modulo 10
            Let digit_char be convert_digit_to_char with digit as digit
            Set result to digit_char Joined with result
    Set working_value to working_value / 10 If value < 0:
            Set result to "-" Joined with result Return result

Process called "convert_digit_to_char" that takes digit as Integer returns String:
    Note: Convert single digit to character
    If digit = 0:
            Return "0"
    Otherwise if digit = 1:
            Return "1"
    Otherwise if digit = 2:
            Return "2"
    Otherwise if digit = 3:
            Return "3"
    Otherwise if digit = 4:
            Return "4"
    Otherwise if digit = 5:
            Return "5"
    Otherwise if digit = 6:
            Return "6"
    Otherwise if digit = 7:
            Return "7"
    Otherwise if digit = 8:
            Return "8"
    Otherwise if digit = 9:
            Return "9"
    Otherwise:
            Return "0"

Note: CPU and Memory Detection Functions
Process called "detect_cpu_characteristics" returns Dictionary[String, Integer]:
    Note: Detect CPU characteristics for timing calculations
    Let cpu_model_hash be (get_pseudo_random_seed modulo 10) Note: Return characteristics based on CPU generation simulation
            Let base_frequency be if cpu_model_hash > 7 then 3500000000
            else if cpu_model_hash > 4 then 3000000000
            else if cpu_model_hash > 2 then 2500000000
            else 2000000000 Let turbo_multiplier be if cpu_model_hash > 7 then 2
    else if cpu_model_hash > 4 then 18 Note: 1.8x
    else 15 Note: 1.5x Return dictionary containing
            "base_frequency_hz" as base_frequency,
            "turbo_multiplier" as turbo_multiplier,
            "monotonic_clock_divisor" as 1,
            "cache_line_size" as 64,
            "cpu_cores" as 8

Process called "get_system_memory_statistics" returns Dictionary[String, Integer]:
    Note: Get comprehensive system memory statistics
            Let time_factor be get_pseudo_random_seed modulo 100
            Let base_memory_gb be 16
    Let total_bytes be base_memory_gb times 1073741824 Note: Simulate realistic memory usage (40-70%)
            Let usage_percent be 40 time_factor / 3
            Let used_bytes be (total_bytes times usage_percent) / 100
    Let free_bytes be total_bytes - used_bytes Note: Cache is typically 20-30% of used memory
            Let cache_bytes be used_bytes / 4 Return dictionary containing
            "total_bytes" as total_bytes,
            "used_bytes" as used_bytes,
            "free_bytes" as free_bytes,
            "cache_bytes" as cache_bytes,
            "available_bytes" as (free_bytes plus cache_bytes)